    import ibis, pandas, dask, pandas as üêº, pytest, base64



[`ibis`][ibis] is mature open source project that has been in development for __~5__
years with __1342__ ‚≠êÔ∏ègazers.
It provides an interface to SQL for [Python] programmers and 
bridges the gap between remote storage & execution systems using [Python]'s glue language. 
These features provide authors the ability to:

1. Write backend independent [SQL] expressions in [Python].
2. Access different database connections (eg. [sqlite], [omnisci], [pandas]).
3. Visually confirm their expressions with DAGs of their query.

Y'all may consult the [`ibis`][ibis] if you want to [learn more about the design][design].

[`ibis`][ibis] is an alternative approach using databases that relies [Python] rather than [SQL] experience.
Typically, folks would have to learn entirely new syntax,
or a [bespoke flavor of SQL][flavor of sql], to perform even simple tasks in SQL.
Now, those with Python abilities can avoid a steep learning curve
by using the [`ibis`][ibis] producivity framework for composing and executing expressions in [SQL]
by making connections to familiar fluent syntaxes ala [`üêº`][pandas] & [`dask`][dask]. [`ibis`][ibis] also assists in 
composing [SQL] expression by providing rich visual feedback about each [Python] object.

[`ibis`][ibis] has a lot features that we'll reveal over time as we spend time bolstering the 
community and knowledge bases.

## Connecting to a database.

Whenever we speak of databases, we'll need to establish [database connection]. 
`ibis` makes it easy to make different database connections or `client`s. 

    client = ibis.sqlite.connect('lahmansbaseballdb.sqlite')
    
<br/>
`client` is a connection to our [‚öæÔ∏è database][data].
    
    
The [‚öæÔ∏è database][data] has __29__ tables and below are some of their names.

    >>> client.list_tables()
    [...'appearances'...'halloffame', 'homegames', 'leagues', 'managers',...]

## Selecting and visualizing tables.

A data frame can be created from `ibis` expressions like the example above for the `halloffame` table. To demonstrate some of `ibis`'s capabilities we'll discuss information in the `halloffame` and `appearances` tables.

    halloffame, appearances = client.table('halloffame'), client.table('appearances')

<br/>
A feature of Ibis is a visual DAG representation of our SQL query using graphviz, `dask` users will be familiar with this
feature.

<div class="imageflex" style="display:flex;"><img src="data:image/png;base64,"/><img src="data:image/png;base64,"/></div>

A table does not hold any data, rather it is an expression that can be appended to manipulate data in a database.

    >>> assert isinstance(halloffame, ibis.expr.types.TableExpr)

    sample = halloffame.head()
    
Looking at a `sample` expression we can reveal the SQL query we constructed.
    
    >>> str(sample.compile())
    'SELECT t0."ID", t0."playerID",...FROM base.halloffame AS t0...LIMIT ? OFFSET ?'
    
And, we can execute the expression to return a `üêº.DataFrame`.
    
    >>> assert isinstance(sample.execute(), üêº.DataFrame)

    sample.execute()
    



## Filtering and selecting data.

`ibis` uses familiar `pandas` syntax to build SQL queries.
Our first selection will that filters only the players from our data by applying the `predicate` to the `halloffame` expression.
    
    predicate = halloffame.category == 'Player'
    players = halloffame[predicate]
    
<div class="imageflex" style="display:flex;"><img src="data:image/png;base64,"/></div>  



## Joining [`ibis`][ibis] tables.

A single view `halloffame` players and `appearances` requires joining the
two tables. We'll perform an inner join based on the playerID column.
    
    predicate = players.playerID == appearances.playerID
    
These tables share columns, but SQL does not like overlapping columns.
    
    columns = [x for x in appearances.columns if x not in {'playerID', 'ID'}]
    
Composing the join.
    
    unmaterialized = players.join(appearances[columns], predicate)
    
The table is not materialized or held in memory yet.  This is a SQL thing, 
in Python we add the materialize method.

    join = unmaterialized.materialize()
    #unmaterialized.distinct()
    
    join = join.materialize().distinct()  # like üêº.DataFrame.drop_duplicates

## How many pitchers have been inducted into the hall of fame?

Some hitters may have pitched so we'll filter out those appearances.

    pitchers = join[join.G_p > 100]

    inducted_pitchers = pitchers.groupby([pitchers.inducted, pitchers.yearID]).count().execute().set_index('inducted yearID'.split())

    
    fig = inducted_pitchers.loc['Y']['count'].pipe(
        lambda df: df.reindex(range(df.index.min(), df.index.max())).fillna(0)
    ).rename('Inducted pitchers').plot.bar(figsize=(15, 5), grid=True)
